examples: The product is undergoing a change in order to improve it.

definitions.definition: Small denominations of money given in exchange for a larger denomination.
examples: Can I get change for this $100 bill, please?

definitions.definition: Balance of money returned from the sum paid after deducting the price of a purchase .
examples: A customer who pays with a 10-pound note for a £9 item receives one pound in change .

definitions.definition: An amount of cash , usually in the form of coins , but sometimes inclusive of paper money.
examples: Do you have any change on you? I need to make a phone call.
This bus ride requires exact change .
The train journey from Bristol to Nottingham includes a change at Birmingham.

definitions.definition: Any order in which a number of bells are struck, other than that of the diatonic scale.

main_definition: ( countable , uncountable ) The process of becoming different .
secondary_definitions: ( uncountable ) Small denominations of money given in exchange for a larger denomination.
( uncountable ) Balance of money returned from the sum paid after deducting the price of a purchase .
( uncountable ) An amount of cash , usually in the form of coins , but sometimes inclusive of paper money.
( campanology ) Any order in which a number of bells are struck, other than that of the diatonic scale.
( Scotland , dated ) A public house ; an alehouse .
